article.headline: Vanderbilt outrebounds LSU 41-32
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Carla Thomas had the game plan down pat
-- take her shots and grab the rebounds.

She did just that, recording her ninth double-digit scoring game
of the season with 22 points and 11 rebounds, and Vanderbilt upset
LSU 61-55 Thursday night.

"We knew what we had to do," Thomas said. "And a big part of
the game plan was to outrebound this team."

LSU (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) was without coach Sue Gunter, who will miss the rest of the
games because of lung problems and acute bronchitis. Gunter will
continue to participate in film sessions and practices at her own
discretion for the Lady Tigers.

"I'd like to blame that for the loss," said acting LSU coach
Pokey Chatman. "But it wasn't that. We just didn't play the way we
should have."

Vanderbilt (17-7, 5-6 Southeastern Conference) was aggressive
offensively. Both teams shot 40 percent, but the Commodores made
5-of-13 3-pointers to LSU's 2-of-7, and 14 second-chance points to
five for the Tigers.

"It was tough just to get the ball," LSU guard Seimone
Augustus said. "They really blocked out and went to the boards. We
knew they were going to be aggressive and they were."

The Commodores also were tenacious defensively. They
outrebounded LSU 41-32, allowing the Tigers only eight offensive
boards. Vanderbilt had 11 steals to LSU's seven.

LSU (20-5, 8-3) had won 13 straight home games -- the second
longest streak in the SEC. The Tigers also had won five straight
going into the game. Vanderbilt had lost four in a row.

Abi Ramsey scored 17 points for Vanderbilt including 5-of-9
3-point shots.

"We knew if we ran our offense and executed I was going to be
open," Ramsey said.

Augustus led LSU with 18 points, but took only three shots in
the second half. Temeka Johnson had 14, and Wendlyn Jones 10.

Jones cut the Commodores' lead to three points, hitting a pair
of free throws with 3:06 left. But a 3-pointer by Ramsey made it
56-50 with 2:17 remaining, and the Commodores were never in trouble
after that.

Vanderbilt did not look like a slumping team in the first half.
Although LSU tied the score twice, the Commodores led for most of
the half, and held a 33-24 edge at the break.

"We could have buried ourselves, especially after losing four
in a row," said Vanderbilt coach Melanie Balcomb. "But we weren't
going to do that."
